{
  "masechta": "Gittin",
  "daf": 89,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Rav Ashi on the Substantiation of Kol (Rumor) and the Evidentiary Requirements for Acting Upon It",
      "display_title": "Kol & Substantiation",
      "timestamp": "00:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Ashi's principle: A kol that Beit Din has not established is not considered a kol",
          "display_title": "Kol Requires Beit Din",
          "timestamp": "00:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kol after marriage (kol achar nissuin) is not heeded; kol after betrothal (erusin) is debated",
          "display_title": "Kol After Marriage",
          "timestamp": "00:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Chaviva and the final halakha: Rumor even after erusin is not heeded once married",
          "display_title": "Rav Chaviva Ruling",
          "timestamp": "03:18"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of Competing Marriage Rumors: Woman Rumored Married to Reuven, Then Marries Shimon with Known Kiddushin",
      "display_title": "Kol & Kiddushin",
      "timestamp": "03:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The query from Rav's house to Shmuel: If a woman has a rumor of marriage to Reuven and Shimon marries her with explicit kiddushin, what is the ruling?",
          "display_title": "Query Setup",
          "timestamp": "03:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel's response: Tatze (she must leave Shimon); investigation is required; if the first marriage is invalid, the kol can be negated; if valid, no get from Shimon is needed",
          "display_title": "Shmuel's Response",
          "timestamp": "04:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Dispute with Rav Huna's principle: A married woman accepting kiddushin is akin to declaring her divorce; in Nahardea (Shmuel's place), kol is not negated even if investigation reveals it false",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna Dispute",
          "timestamp": "09:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Clarification of Rav Hamnuna's teaching: Declaration of divorce only carries weight if made in the presence of the first husband; absence does not vitiate her obligation to the first",
          "display_title": "Rav Hamnuna Presence",
          "timestamp": "10:42"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of Unsubstantiated Rumor: Investigation Yields No Clear Resolution",
      "display_title": "Rumor Unresolved",
      "timestamp": "13:02",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna's position: Force Reuven to divorce her so she may marry Shimon, but do not permit Shimon to divorce her (concern for appearance of machzir grushato)",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna Option",
          "timestamp": "13:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ameimar's position: The Rabbis resolved that she remains married to the first by retroactively invalidating the second marriage as an error, avoiding the appearance of machzir grushato",
          "display_title": "Ameimar Resolution",
          "timestamp": "15:21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of Two Competing Rumors: Woman Rumored Married to Both Reuven and Shimon",
      "display_title": "Competing Rumors",
      "timestamp": "18:03",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Papa's initial position: Following Rav Huna, she is limited to the same options (Reuven divorces her to Shimon; not vice versa)",
          "display_title": "Rav Papa Initial",
          "timestamp": "18:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ameimar's rebuttal: With two rumors, concern for machzir grushato does not apply; she is permitted to both and may stay with Reuven if one rumor is shown false",
          "display_title": "Ameimar Two Rumors",
          "timestamp": "18:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "The halakha: When rumors conflict and are unresolved, both men are disqualified; no machzir grushato concern applies to two rumors",
          "display_title": "Two Rumors Ruling",
          "timestamp": "18:47"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Transition to Tzadi: The Grounds for Divorce in the Mishna",
      "display_title": "Grounds for Divorce",
      "timestamp": "19:37",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Mishna begins with grounds for divorce: Beit Shammai requires ervas davar (sexual sin) as the sole justification",
          "display_title": "Beit Shammai",
          "timestamp": "19:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Beit Hillel permits divorce for any matter that displeases the husband, even burning his food",
          "display_title": "Beit Hillel Leniency",
          "timestamp": "22:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva extends even further: divorce is permitted even if he finds another woman more beautiful, based on the husband not finding favor in her eyes",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva Permissive",
          "timestamp": "24:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara Analysis of Mishna Dispute: Linguistic Interpretation of 'Ervas Davar' vs. 'Davar'",
      "display_title": "Textual Analysis",
      "timestamp": "26:29",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Beit Hillel's argument: The pasuk must specify both 'ervas' and 'davar' to teach that divorce is permitted for sexual sin AND for any matter",
          "display_title": "Beit Hillel Exegesis",
          "timestamp": "26:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Beit Shammai's response: The word 'davar' serves to indicate the requirement of two witnesses to establish ervas davar (adultery)",
          "display_title": "Beit Shammai Witnesses",
          "timestamp": "28:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Linguistic debate continues: Determination that Beit Shammai reads 'ervas davar' as one unified concept (adultery), while Beit Hillel reads them as two separate grounds",
          "display_title": "One vs. Two Grounds",
          "timestamp": "29:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Post-Mishna Questions: Validity of Get Without Just Cause and Marital Obligations",
      "display_title": "Get Validity Issues",
      "timestamp": "32:14",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Papa's question: If a man divorces without any justification (no ervas davar, no davar), is the get valid or must he remarry her?",
          "display_title": "Unjustified Divorce",
          "timestamp": "32:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's response citing the rapist's law: The Torah prohibits remarriage of a rape victim (lo yuchal leshalcha), but outside that context a get is valid even if not warranted",
          "display_title": "Get Effective",
          "timestamp": "32:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Mesharshiya's ethical concern: A man who secretly plans divorce while his wife serves him commits a betrayal akin to plotting against a trusting friend",
          "display_title": "Secret Divorce Plan",
          "timestamp": "33:13"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaitic Teaching: Classification of Men and Their Standards for Wives Using Food Analogy",
      "display_title": "Food & Wife Analogy",
      "timestamp": "34:25",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir's analogy: Just as men differ in tolerance toward contaminated food, they differ in standards for wives; illustrates fastidious vs. permissive attitudes",
          "display_title": "Analogy Framework",
          "timestamp": "34:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "The fastidious man locks his wife indoors to prevent any contamination; this creates jealousy and enmity, actually leading to infidelity",
          "display_title": "Fastidious Type",
          "timestamp": "35:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "The normal man tolerates his wife's interactions with others; the permissive man is indifferent even to obvious impropriety",
          "display_title": "Normal & Permissive",
          "timestamp": "37:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Halakha of Divorce for Improper Conduct: Women's Immodest Behavior as Grounds",
      "display_title": "Immodest Conduct",
      "timestamp": "39:09",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Enumeration of behaviors constituting ervas davar: uncovered head, spinning in marketplace, slitted clothing, bathing in same place as men",
          "display_title": "Improper Behaviors",
          "timestamp": "39:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "These behaviors are deemed mitzva min hatorah to divorce; framed as dat Moshe and dat Yehudi (religious and Jewish community standards)",
          "display_title": "Mitzva to Divorce",
          "timestamp": "39:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Midrashic interpretation of pasuk: The second husband who marries a divorced woman is foolish; she will 'bury him' by dying or bringing destruction",
          "display_title": "Second Husband Fate",
          "timestamp": "40:35"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaitic Dispute: Reading Malachi on Divorce ('Shnui Hashaleiach') — First vs. Second Marriage",
      "display_title": "Malachi Dispute",
      "timestamp": "42:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda: 'If you hate her, send her away' (permissive approach, aligned with Rabbi Akiva or Beit Hillel)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda",
          "timestamp": "42:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan: 'The one who sends her away is hateful' (restrictive approach, aligned with Beit Shammai)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yochanan",
          "timestamp": "42:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative girsa: 'Only if she is hated by God should you send her away' (only adultery justifies divorce)",
          "display_title": "God's Hate Standard",
          "timestamp": "43:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: The tannaim do not disagree; rather, Rabbi Yehuda speaks of second marriage, Rabbi Yochanan of first marriage",
          "display_title": "Marriage Distinction",
          "timestamp": "43:16"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Midrash on First Marriage: The Altar's Lament and the Covenant of Partnership",
      "display_title": "First Marriage Sanctity",
      "timestamp": "43:27",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Elazar: Divorcing one's first wife causes the altar itself to weep; even the altar mourns this tragedy",
          "display_title": "Altar's Tears",
          "timestamp": "43:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Midrashic basis: The pasuk (Malachi 2) describes the covering of God's altar with tears when a man betrays his wife of youth",
          "display_title": "Malachi Midrash",
          "timestamp": "43:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Theological meaning: Betrayal of one's wife ruptures the relationship with God; the first wife is 'your friend and wife of your covenant'",
          "display_title": "Covenant Rupture",
          "timestamp": "44:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Contemporary application: Balancing the principle (do not divorce trivially) with modern reality; need for judicial sensitivity in divorce proceedings",
          "display_title": "Modern Balance",
          "timestamp": "45:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Closing image of partnership: Historical ketubot use 'chevratcha v'eishet britcha' (your friend and wife of covenant), affirming equal partnership in marriage",
          "display_title": "Partnership Ideal",
          "timestamp": "46:51"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
